‘With numerous chocolate-box villages spread across the South West, it is little wonder the majority of Brits would position their ideal home there.’

Mr Hall said the high price of a home in London, with some selling for tens of millions of pounds each, jars with the fact that so many people do not want to actually live there.

He added: ‘London is home to some of the most expensive prime properties in the world. High-spec townhouses, mansions and apartments attract some of the wealthiest buyers from across the globe.

‘But the bright lights of city-life appear less attractive for the majority of Brits who see their ideal home in a rural idyll 200 miles away.’

London fared poorly in the survey, with just 14 per cent saying it is their ideal location

It comes at a time that the average home in the countryside is already around £200,000, around £30,000 more expensive than a home in an urban area, according to the banking giant Halifax.

With an average full-time salary of £26,500, millions of people cannot afford to buy in either the city or the countryside, forcing soaring numbers of people to rent or live with their parents.

Primelocation.com is part of Zoopla Property Group, a privately held company whose shareholders include A&N Media, a division of the Daily Mail and General Trust.

